<LegalPage locale="en" title="Security & disclosure" lastUpdated="2026-05-20" path="/legal/security">
  <p>
    Keyfount is a security-sensitive tool. This page summarises the
    threat model the extension is designed for and how to report a
    vulnerability.
  </p>

  <h2>Threat model</h2>
  <p>
    The extension is designed to protect against the following threats:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Vault leaks.</strong> There is no vault. Derived passwords are
      computed on demand and never stored.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Sync-service compromise.</strong> The extension never syncs
      anything to a remote service. Local data stays on the device.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Network observers.</strong> The extension performs zero network
      calls.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Reused per-site passwords.</strong> Derived passwords are
      unique per site by construction, so a leak from one site cannot be
      replayed against another.
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The extension does <strong>not</strong> protect against:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      A compromised device — a keylogger or malware running with your user
      rights can read your master password while you type it.
    </li>
    <li>
      A weak master password — a brute-force attacker who recovers a derived
      password from a breached site and knows the email/domain inputs can
      attempt to recover the master offline. Argon2id raises the cost
      substantially, but a short or common master is still recoverable.
    </li>
    <li>
      Phishing — the extension fills passwords on the active tab, including
      look-alike domains. Confirm the URL bar before filling.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Cryptography</h2>
  <p>
    Key derivation uses <a
      href="https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc9106"
      target="_blank"
      rel="noopener noreferrer">Argon2id (RFC 9106)</a
    >, the memory-hard function recommended by OWASP for password hashing.
    Parameters: 3 iterations, 64 MiB of memory, parallelism 1, 32-byte output.
    The salt is built from the registrable site domain, the email used at
    that site, and a per-site counter. The output is then shaped into a
    password matching the per-site profile.
  </p>

  <h2>Reporting a vulnerability</h2>
  <p>
    If you believe you have found a security vulnerability in the extension,
    the website, or the cryptographic construction, please report it
    privately rather than opening a public issue.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      Use GitHub's private vulnerability reporting at <a
        href="https://github.com/Keyfount/extension/security/advisories/new"
        target="_blank"
        rel="noopener noreferrer">github.com/Keyfount/extension/security/advisories/new</a
      >.
    </li>
    <li>
      Include a clear description, reproduction steps, and the affected
      version (visible in the extension's "About" panel).
    </li>
    <li>
      We acknowledge new reports within 7 days and aim to publish a fix
      within 90 days of confirmation. Coordinated disclosure is appreciated.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Reproducible builds</h2>
  <p>
    Extension releases are tagged in the repository, and the bundle published
    to the Chrome Web Store is built from the corresponding tag. To verify a
    release yourself, check out the tag, run the documented build command, and
    compare the resulting bundle against the one shipped by the store.
  </p>
</LegalPage>
